Two-beam propagation in space and spatial shake display

In the example, two Gaussian beams with different wavelengths are placed. Both are located at the origin and are propagated to a plane 5 cm in the Z direction.

To observe different patterns go to the Gaussian Beam 2 [0] component and in the BaseBeam property, modify the Lambda parameter.

Insert simulation components

To place the components in the logic, two Gaussian Beam, one Add Fields, one Inspection Plane must be inserted from the BPM tab. To convert the beams to an intensity map, you must insert the To Fresnel component found in the BPM tab. The component in the logic editor appears with the name Beam Field to Matrix.

To view the Fresnel plane you must go to the Fresnel tab and add the View(t) component

The components are joined following the logic indicated in the first image of this documentation. By modifying the properties of the Beam Field to Matrix component you can improve the spatial resolution. Keep in mind that the higher the resolution, the longer the computing time. Some common configurations can be seen in the following image.

Field display

The component allows you to visualize the Fresnel field on the inspection plane as a function of time. The settings can be accessed by clicking on the component in the node editor (Logic Tab).

The following image contains the properties of the component.

The component properties are as follows:

  • Computation: Establishes whether the calculation of the fields is carried out during the simulation, or when you want to view it. Initially located inWhen_Needed in order to optimize simulation times.
  • Name:  Contains the name that is observed in the simulation logic (Logic tab) and in the component's own visualization tab.
  • Generate_Image: Allows you to modify the simulation logic and generate an image listing component that can be saved in a video.
  • Image_Height y Image_Width: Width and height of the image to be generated yesGenerate_Image = true.
  • Start_Time y End_Time: Establishes the initial and final time that will be used for the temporal calculation of the field. Found in seconds.
  • Steps: Number of moments of time to calculate.
  • Fix_Limits: Indicates whether the color scale is adjusted dynamically at each instant of time, or takes into account the maximum value in the simulation.
  • Interpolate: Allows you to interpolate the calculated points to smooth the final image.
  • Visualization_Time: Time in which each time instant is displayed in the window. It does not represent simulation time. It is found in [ms].
  • Visualization_Component: Indicates whether the module, phase, imaginary or real component of the field is displayed.

More documentation can be seen athttps://github.com/EmilianoJan/OpticStudioDev/wiki
